Headline.Para: Larry Nassar's Ex-Boss Accused of Soliciting Sexual Acts From Students; William Strampel was charged with criminal sexual conduct and neglect of duty

LeadPara.Para: William Strampel, the former dean of Michigan State University's College of Osteopathic Medicine and longtime boss of convicted sexual abuser Larry Nassar, was charged Tuesday with counts including criminal sexual conduct and neglect of duty, according to court filings.

The charges stem in part from allegations by female students at the school, who told investigators that Dr. Strampel used the power of his office to proposition them for sexual acts, grope them and harass them, according to an affidavit filed Tuesday in Michigan state court. They also relate to Dr. Strampel's alleged failure to supervise Dr. Nassar, allowing him to see and abuse patients while under investigation for sexual misconduct and for two years afterward.

TailParas.Para: Dr. Strampel, 70 years old, was arrested Monday. The charges filed Tuesday morning in a Michigan district court in East Lansing include one count of fourth-degree criminal sexual conduct using force or coercion and two misdemeanor counts of willful neglect of duty by a public officer.
He is also facing a felony charge of misconduct of a public official, which carries up to five years in prison.

Dr. Strampel was arraigned Tuesday afternoon, with bond set at $25,000, and wasn't asked to enter a plea. He appeared via video feed from the Ingham County Jail, his hands cuffed. He was told not to have any contact with witnesses or victims, or to initiate contact with any current or former Michigan State medical student.

John Dakmak, an attorney for Dr. Strampel who appeared in the courtroom Tuesday, didn't immediately respond to a request for comment. In court, he said Dr. Strampel "is not a threat to the public at large."

The Michigan Attorney General's office seized Dr. Strampel's computer in early February, as part of its investigation into the school's handling of complaints against Dr. Nassar, according to the affidavit. On the computer, investigators found approximately 50 photos of "bare vaginas, nude and seminude women, sex toys, and pornography," the affidavit says.

Also on the work computer were pornographic videos and a video of Dr. Nassar performing "treatment" on a young female patient, according to the affidavit. More than 250 women have alleged that Dr. Nassar sexually abused them in the guise of medical treatment, in which he pressed his bare hands against their vaginal and anal areas.

Dr. Nassar long defended his techniques as legitimate medical treatment, but in his guilty plea on state sexual-abuse charges last year, Dr. Nassar said he performed the "treatments" for his sexual gratification.

The charges against Dr. Strampel come as media and law enforcement have been looking into the culture and possible misconduct at the school of osteopathic medicine during Dr. Strampel's 15-year tenure. The inquiries stem, in part, from allegations that the university, and in particular Dr. Nassar's direct colleagues, didn't do enough to prevent Dr. Nassar from abusing patients.

As dean of the college, the affidavit says, "Strampel abused the authority of his public office, through threats and manipulation, to solicit, receive, and possess pornographic images of women who appear to be MSU students in violation of his statutory duty as a public officer."

In a statement, Interim President John Engler said Tuesday that the university would continue to cooperate with all official investigations related to sexual assault or other misconduct. He said of Dr. Strampel, "Some of the allegations about his personal conduct, especially conduct toward students, are disturbing. Today's charges confirm our belief that he has fallen short of what is expected and required from academic leadership."

According to the affidavit, Dr. Strampel allowed Dr. Nassar to see patients during a 2014 Title IX investigation into a patient's complaint of possible sexual misconduct by Dr. Nassar. Dr. Nassar was cleared in that investigation, but the school gave him guidelines to prevent future complaints. According to the affidavit, Dr. Strampel didn't monitor Dr. Nassar and allowed him to begin seeing patients again before the investigation was completed.

The two willful neglect charges against Dr. Strampel "apply to his supervision or, quite frankly, his lack of supervision of Larry Nassar," said Bill Forsyth, the special prosecutor overseeing the attorney general's investigation, at a press conference Tuesday.

Dr. Nassar, who worked at Michigan State University for nearly two decades and served as a volunteer team doctor for the U.S. women's national gymnastics team, was fired by Michigan State in September 2016. In November 2016, he was arrested on state sexual-abuse charges, and in December 2016 he was charged with federal child-pornography counts. He later pleaded guilty to the state and federal charges and is currently serving a 60-year sentence on the pornography counts.

The Wall Street Journal reported earlier this month that Dr. Strampel had told a group of students and administrators in October 2016—a month after Michigan State fired Dr. Nassar—that he didn't believe the women and girls who accused Dr. Nassar of sexual abuse, according to two people who said they were present at the meeting.

"Patients lie to get doctors in trouble," Dr. Strampel was reported as saying. "I don't think any of these women were actually assaulted by Larry…As soon as I found out, I had to fire his ass. I didn't want to, but what am I supposed to do?"
Through another lawyer representing him in the civil cases, Dr. Strampel declined at the time to comment on those remarks.

The Journal also reported that Dr. Strampel had asked a student to perform a rectal exam on him in 2005, according to a memo written by individuals in that class and shared with a longtime faculty member shortly after the alleged incident.

According to the affidavit filed Tuesday, in 2010 and 2014, Dr. Strampel allegedly grabbed the buttocks of two women at school events. He also allegedly told one female student in 2014 that she could do a "favor"—including responding if he called her to his home on the weekend—in exchange for the opportunity to retake a test.
University officials said last month they are in the process of trying to fire Dr. Strampel from the faculty.

Dr. Strampel, who led the osteopathic medical school from 2002 until he took medical leave and stepped down as dean in December, has been named as a defendant in civil lawsuits brought by many of the roughly 250 women and girls who were allegedly abused by Dr. Nassar. Attorneys for Dr. Strampel have declined to comment on pending litigation.
